WEBVTT

1
00:00:00.792 --> 00:00:04.421
Our best classical supercomputers are growing more powerful,

2
00:00:04.629 --> 00:00:08.675
and we're becoming better at computation, including simulating systems.

3
00:00:09.050 --> 00:00:13.388
But simulating nature is a very difficult problem in general.

4
00:00:14.055 --> 00:00:18.018
My name is Victoria Lipinska and today we'll explore one of the algorithms

5
00:00:18.018 --> 00:00:21.646
that could make simulating nature possible on a quantum computer.

6
00:00:22.689 --> 00:00:25.692
Let's start with an example and consider caffeine.

7
00:00:26.192 --> 00:00:27.736
It's a simple molecule.

8
00:00:27.736 --> 00:00:31.906
To represent the energy configuration of just one molecule of caffeine,

9
00:00:32.115 --> 00:00:35.326
we'd need approximately ten to the power of 48 bits.

10
00:00:35.827 --> 00:00:38.580
That's ten with 48 zeros

11
00:00:38.580 --> 00:00:41.666
and its about 10% of the number of atoms in the earth.

12
00:00:42.834 --> 00:00:44.044
And it actually gets worse.

13
00:00:44.044 --> 00:00:48.465
If you have 125 orbitals and you want to store all possible

14
00:00:48.465 --> 00:00:51.009
configurations, you need more memory

15
00:00:51.009 --> 00:00:54.387
in your classical computer than there are atoms in the universe.

16
00:00:55.138 --> 00:00:57.932
That's impossible to represent with supercomputers.

17
00:00:58.391 --> 00:01:00.560
There is hope for quantum computers, though,

18
00:01:00.810 --> 00:01:03.813
because they're intrinsically good at simulating nature.

19
00:01:04.188 --> 00:01:06.900
For a caffeine molecule, that would mean representing

20
00:01:06.900 --> 00:01:09.903
the system using 160 qubits.

21
00:01:10.320 --> 00:01:13.115
That sounds much more manageable.

22
00:01:13.490 --> 00:01:17.202
Various quantum algorithms have been proposed that allow

23
00:01:17.202 --> 00:01:20.497
smaller quantum computers to heuristically simulate nature.

24
00:01:21.039 --> 00:01:24.667
Enter: variational quantum eigensolver or VQE.

25
00:01:25.877 --> 00:01:28.755
VQE is an algorithm that runs partly on a quantum

26
00:01:28.755 --> 00:01:31.800
computer and partly on a classical computer.

27
00:01:32.175 --> 00:01:35.887
It allows us to find values that solve a given optimization problem.

28
00:01:35.887 --> 00:01:39.974
VQE is very closely related to other methods involving

29
00:01:39.974 --> 00:01:44.979
variation of parameters like the quantum approximate optimization algorithm.

30
00:01:44.979 --> 00:01:49.233
Identifying applications of VQE in your industry or research

31
00:01:49.234 --> 00:01:53.780
is something of an art, but there are loose guidelines.

32
00:01:53.780 --> 00:01:57.450
Generally, VQE is applicable to problems that can be cast

33
00:01:57.450 --> 00:02:00.912
as an optimization problem with continuous variables.

34
00:02:01.371 --> 00:02:04.582
This is the case, for example, in much of quantum chemistry.

35
00:02:05.083 --> 00:02:09.087
Very often, in chemistry, we're interested in the ground state.

36
00:02:09.296 --> 00:02:12.924
The ground state is the state of lowest energy of the system.

37
00:02:12.924 --> 00:02:16.219
In order to find the ground state energy, VQE explores

38
00:02:16.219 --> 00:02:19.389
the energy for different configurations of the system

39
00:02:19.389 --> 00:02:22.392
and looks for the lowest energy configuration.

40
00:02:23.017 --> 00:02:27.272
At a high level, VQE takes in a description of the quantum system

41
00:02:27.689 --> 00:02:30.525
and looks for the lowest energy.

42
00:02:30.525 --> 00:02:33.361
It does this by varying the configuration of the system.

43
00:02:33.611 --> 00:02:35.864
and looks for the lowest energy.

44
00:02:36.573 --> 00:02:40.368
To start, we have to input an appropriate description of the system

45
00:02:40.869 --> 00:02:45.081
that the quantum computer understands and a set of parameters describing it

46
00:02:45.248 --> 00:02:46.249
which will be optimized.

47
00:02:47.292 --> 00:02:48.293
The quantum part of

48
00:02:48.293 --> 00:02:51.171
the algorithm prepares the system in a state

49
00:02:51.421 --> 00:02:55.549
described by a given set of parameters and calculates the energy.

50
00:02:55.550 --> 00:02:58.428
While the classical part is responsible

51
00:02:58.428 --> 00:03:01.639
for optimizing those parameters at each step.

52
00:03:02.015 --> 00:03:04.851
This quantum classical process is repeated

53
00:03:04.851 --> 00:03:07.228
until we reach the lowest energy.

54
00:03:08.229 --> 00:03:10.982
Let's now zoom in on what's going on under the hood.

55
00:03:11.399 --> 00:03:15.153
The energy configuration is typically described in the Hamiltonian

56
00:03:15.320 --> 00:03:18.281
and typically it's a really big matrix.

57
00:03:18.615 --> 00:03:22.076
In algebra, to find the lowest eigenvalue of the matrix

58
00:03:22.076 --> 00:03:24.913
corresponding to the lowest energy of the system,

59
00:03:25.246 --> 00:03:28.708
we would simply do singular value decomposition.

60
00:03:29.250 --> 00:03:33.880
However, the matrices we'll be looking at are exponentially large

61
00:03:34.088 --> 00:03:37.967
and it's an exponentially difficult problem to do this algebraically.

62
00:03:38.801 --> 00:03:41.763
This Hamiltonian has to be represented in the form

63
00:03:41.971 --> 00:03:44.474
that the quantum computer can understand.

64
00:03:44.807 --> 00:03:49.270
So translated from chemistry language to quantum computing language.

65
00:03:49.938 --> 00:03:51.940
No worries on the details though.

66
00:03:51.940 --> 00:03:56.527
Ultimately there is this programable ways to translate the Hamiltonian usually

67
00:03:56.527 --> 00:04:01.407
seen in chemistry into a Hamiltonian understandable for a quantum computer.

68
00:04:02.408 --> 00:04:03.493
We then input this

69
00:04:03.493 --> 00:04:07.455
Hamiltonian together with the circuit, which we call a variational form.

70
00:04:08.289 --> 00:04:11.709
Choosing a variational form is something of an art.

71
00:04:11.834 --> 00:04:12.669
Again,

72
00:04:12.669 --> 00:04:16.880
it represents our best guess on what the quantum state of the system could be.

73
00:04:17.673 --> 00:04:21.511
This variational circuit is parameterized with a set of parameters theta,

74
00:04:21.761 --> 00:04:25.765
and we also input an initial choice of these parameters.

75
00:04:26.182 --> 00:04:29.978
Based on this, the quantum part of VQE:

76
00:04:29.978 --> 00:04:33.856
prepares the reference state, for example, the zero state;

77
00:04:33.856 --> 00:04:39.028
uses a parameterized quantum circuit, the variational form, to prepare a quantum

78
00:04:39.028 --> 00:04:44.492
state for an initial guess of parameters on the quantum computer; and it estimates

79
00:04:44.492 --> 00:04:49.289
the energy corresponding to the state evaluated through the Hamiltonian.

80
00:04:49.789 --> 00:04:51.958
This energy estimate is then fed

81
00:04:51.958 --> 00:04:56.337
into the classical optimizer, which finds a new set of parameters.

82
00:04:56.754 --> 00:05:00.258
The parameters make their way back to the quantum solver again,

83
00:05:00.466 --> 00:05:02.927
and the whole process is repeated.

84
00:05:03.344 --> 00:05:06.306
The quantum computer finds a new energy estimate, the

85
00:05:06.306 --> 00:05:10.184
classical optimizer finds a new set of parameters and so on.

86
00:05:10.893 --> 00:05:14.230
We repeat this process until the solution converges.

87
00:05:14.439 --> 00:05:18.401
That means until the difference in outcomes between steps is small enough

88
00:05:18.651 --> 00:05:19.902
for our needs.

89
00:05:19.902 --> 00:05:23.531
At the end, the algorithm returns that minimized energy.

90
00:05:24.407 --> 00:05:26.284
Okay, this is great.

91
00:05:26.284 --> 00:05:29.704
But you might wonder how do we know that this actually works

92
00:05:29.704 --> 00:05:34.500
and that we won't accidentally find energy lower than what we're looking for?

93
00:05:35.501 --> 00:05:37.003
That's a great question.

94
00:05:37.003 --> 00:05:40.423
It turns out that we can never estimate an energy that's lower.

95
00:05:40.757 --> 00:05:44.594
This is thanks to something that we call a variational principle.

96
00:05:45.178 --> 00:05:48.348
The variational principle states that the greatest lower

97
00:05:48.348 --> 00:05:51.517
bound on the energy of the system is always its

98
00:05:51.517 --> 00:05:54.687
lowest energy corresponding to that ground state.

99
00:05:55.146 --> 00:05:59.692
This means that energy evaluated on any other state of that system

100
00:05:59.859 --> 00:06:02.695
will always be greater than the lowest energy.

101
00:06:03.237 --> 00:06:07.033
Therefore, with VQE we can never obtain something

102
00:06:07.033 --> 00:06:09.285
lower than the ground state energy.

103
00:06:09.285 --> 00:06:12.080
However, we can indeed converge to something

104
00:06:12.080 --> 00:06:14.707
greater than the minimum we're looking for.

105
00:06:15.124 --> 00:06:17.710
This is oftentimes called a metastable solution

106
00:06:18.461 --> 00:06:22.173
and its a challenge that researchers try to solve on a daily basis.

107
00:06:23.257 --> 00:06:26.511
VQE is useful because it uses shallower circuits

108
00:06:26.511 --> 00:06:30.348
compared to other protocols that allow us to estimate ground state energy.

109
00:06:30.765 --> 00:06:34.268
This makes it suitable for near-term quantum hardware.

110
00:06:35.019 --> 00:06:38.981
In this video, we had a glimpse of what VQE can do and how it's built.

111
00:06:39.273 --> 00:06:42.485
But I encourage you to explore Qiskit in this context.

112
00:06:42.860 --> 00:06:45.696
Even though we're still at the beginning of our quantum journey,

113
00:06:45.822 --> 00:06:49.617
you might already find it useful for problems you're trying to solve.

114
00:06:50.243 --> 00:06:53.204
My name is Victoria Lipinska and this was an overview

115
00:06:53.204 --> 00:06:57.082
of the variational quantum eigensolver algorithm.
